Breif Introduction

I have summarized in this R Markdown document a bioinformatic pipeline for the analysis of amplicon Illumina reads.

pipeline target -> ITS or 16S rRNA MiSeq PE reads

The pipeline is customized to analyse libraries performed according Lundberg et al. 2013 Nature Methods with some modification.

A little more on the PCR library

Our libriary is made of 3 consecutive PCRs of usually 10, 10 and 15 cycles.

  • first PCR to amplify target DNA e.g., using ITS1F/ITS4;
  • second PCR to add a tail and frame-shifts;
  • third PCR to add illumina adapters and barcodes.

After PCRs are performed, products are

  • normalized to standard concentration (~ 1-2 ng/uL);
  • pooled and concentrated to be (~ 10-20 ng/uL);
  • cleaned up using ampure magnetic beads;
  • quantified on BioAnalyzer before sequencing on the Illumina MiSeq Illumina Analyzer.

Before starting

It is important to check the quality of the files transfer if you are downloading the file from a server/ftp and only after unzipping the reads files.

md5sum *.fastq.gz > md5sum.txt
gunzip *.fastq.gz

Our library consists on 3 files:

  • forward read file *_R1_001.fastq
  • reverse read file *_R2_001.fastq
  • index file *_I1_001.fastq

The FASTQ format

The Illumina output sequencing format is FASTQ which is characterized by four lines per read.

More details

  • Line 1 begins with a “@” character and is followed by a unique sequence identifier and a description (run ID, flowcell ID, flowcell lane, cooridinates of the cluster…).
  • Line 2 is the raw sequence.
  • Line 3 begins with a “+” character and is optionally followed by the same sequence identifier (and any description) again.
  • Line 4 encodes the quality values (Phred scores) for the sequence in Line 2: it contains exactly the same number of symbols as letters in the sequence at Line 2.

2) error correction - OPTIONAL

Read quality can be “corrected” using different tools that (similarly to the denoising process, standard protocol for 454 read data) aim to corrrect the “noise” of the reads. This step can be accomplished using BayesHammer in the software Spades.

conda activate spades
spades.py --only-error-correction --disable-gzip-output --pe1-1 *R1.fastq --pe1-2 *R2.fastq -o corrected

#Pair-end reads need to be resyinced before contintuing, I use Python for that.
python ~/scripts/fastqCombinePairedEnd.py ~$R1 ~$R2
conda deactivate

A smart apprach

If you are working with huge read files, you can test your error correction on a subset of the raw reads. For the subsetting trick seqtk can be used.

module load GCC/5.4.0-2.26
module load OpenMPI/1.10.3
module load seqtk/1.2

seqtk sample -s100 read1.fastq 10000 > sub1.fastq

Subsetting is a valid stratedy before start working on huge data files, it saves time!

3) dempultiplexing

Reads sorted into different bins acording the barcode sequence (index); Many different tools are available.

I usually perform demultilexing using QIIME

  • you need you raw reads
  • you need you mapping_file.txt

validate the mapping file containing the metadata

conda activate qiime1
validate_mapping_file.py -m mapping_*.txt -o mapping_output
conda deactivate

3) dempultiplexing

splitting the libraries

conda activate qiime1

split_libraries_fastq.py -i *_R1_001.fastq -m mapping_*.txt -b *_I1_001.fastq --store_qual_scores --store_demultiplexed_fastq --barcode_type 10 -o splitted --rev_comp_mapping_barcodes -q 30 --max_barcode_errors 0

conda deactivate

Don't forget! You need to activate the specific environent in anaconda that contain the package you want to use!!!

Then check the resulted files… How?

# visualize the log files and count the reads
cat splitted/*log.txt
grep "^@" -c splitted/seqs.fastq

# validate the demultiplexed fasta
conda activate qiime1
validate_demultiplexed_fasta.py -f splitted/seqs.fna -m mapping_*.txt
conda deactivate

4) stripping primers and illumina adapters

Illumina adapters, sequencng primers and target primers need to be eliminated from the reads before moving further. For this goal a common tool is cutadapt.

conda actovate cutadapt
cutadapt -g CTTGGTCATTTAGAGGAAGTAA -e 0.01 --discard-untrimmed --match-read-wildcards splitted/seqs.fastq > stripped.fastq
conda deactivate

5) Phix decontamination and second quality check

Sequecing facilities add Phix to sequencing libraries in terms of 5-10%. It is basically used for:

  • technical control for clustering reaction (a known amount of phiX should yield a known number of phiX clusters).
  • technical control for sequencing accuracy (on-the-fly alignment to the phiX reference is used to calculate the sequencing error rate).
  • introduction of sequencing diversity in low-complexity libraries (diversity is needed to discriminate clusters and create signal thresholds for base-calling).

When to remove the Phix reads?

We want to remove Phix reads before moving forward with the analysis so we eed to downlaod the Phix genome

module load icc/2018.1.163-GCC-6.4.0-2.28
module load ifort/2018.1.163-GCC-6.4.0-2.28
module load impi/2018.1.163
module load Bowtie2/2.3.4.1

# index the Phix genome
mkdir Phix_check/index
bowtie2-build -f /home/Phix_check/index/phix174_genome.fasta index/my_phix
bowtie2-inspect index/my_phix

# check for Phix contamination by mapping your reads against the Phix genome
bowtie2 -x phix_index/my_phix -U stripped.fastq -t -p 3 --un stripped_nophix.fastq -S stripped_contaminated_align.sam 2> stripped_nophix.log

# quality check again
fastqc ./stripped_nophix.fastq

# reads count
grep "^@" -c stripped_nophix.fastq

if you assemble your reads you should resync them after Phix removal!

6) filtering and trimming - CRUCIAL

You must generate a statistics for a precise and targeted filtering of the reads. For this purpose USEARCH and VSEARCH can be used. In the Robert Edgar website is also available a detailed description based on the UPARSE algorithm (See below).

module load vsearch/2.9.0

vsearch -fastq_stats stripped_nophix.fastq -log stats_result_vsearch.txt

/mnt/research/rdp/public/thirdParty/ usearch10.0.240_i86linux64
-fastq_eestats2 stripped_nophix.fastq -output eestats2_result.txt
-length_cutoffs 100,400,1

6) filtering and trimming - CRUCIAL

Let's filter out reads!

The -fastq_stats differ a little from the -fastq_eestats2. Following those statistics we can decide how to trim in accordance to reads quality and length. 

/mnt/research/rdp/public/thirdParty/ usearch10.0.240_i86linux64 -fastq_filter stripped/stripped_R1.fastq -fastq_maxee 1.0 -fastq_trunclen 244 -fastq_maxns 0 -fastaout filtered/filtered_R1.fasta -fastqout filtered/filtered_R1.fastq

Some useful flags for filtering/trimming

  • fastq_stripleft Delete the first N bases in the read.
  • fastq_maxee Discard reads with > E total expected errors for all bases in the read after any truncation options have been applied.
  • fastq_minlen Discard sequences with < L letters.
  • fastq_maxns k Discard if there are >k Ns in the read.
  • fastq_truncqual N Truncate the read at the first position having quality score <= N, so that all remaining Q scores are >N.

Now check reads quality again

At this point you many want to perform another quality check to be sure that the filtered dataset has the quality you expected.

..and try visually look at the reads!

It is fundamental to visualize the reads (if it is a huge file it can anyway be tricky) with a sequences viewer like Seaview or Tablet.

In this way you can see what you have left!

Now, how do your reads look like?

You may want to remove all the conserved parts present in your reads before moving forward with the clustering process.

# trimming to variable region only
/mnt/research/rdp/public/thirdParty/ usearch10.0.240_i86linux64 -fastq_filter filtered/filtered_R1.fastq -fastq_stripleft 44 -fastaout filtered/trimmed_R1.fasta -fastqout filtered/trimmed_R1.fastq

## another quality check is recommended!
fastqc ./trimmed_R1.fastq

7) dereplication, singleton removal and OTU clustering

At this this point your dataset is ready to be clustered into OTUs represenetative sequences. The number of OTUs obteined can therefore vary according to the clustering algorithm. This pipeline is based on USEARCH that uses the UPARSE algorithm form Edgar R. (2013).

# dereplication

/mnt/research/rdp/public/thirdParty/ usearch10.0.240_i86linux64 -fastx_uniques filtered/trimmed_R1.fastq -fastaout clustered_OTU_ESV/uniques_R1.fasta -sizeout

Remove singletones and cluster OTUs

# cluster OTUs at 97% identity

/mnt/research/rdp/public/thirdParty/ usearch10.0.240_i86linux64 -cluster_otus clustered_OTU_ESV/uniques_R1.fasta -minsize 2 -otus clustered_OTU_ESV/otus_R1.fasta -uparseout clustered_OTU_ESV/uparse_otus_R1.txt -relabel OTU_ --threads 20


The OTU clustering algorhitm contains a strong chimera detection so that can be not necessary to further use a reference.

Remove for chimeras sequences

# chimera check against a reference

vsearch -uchime_ref otus.fasta -nonchimeras otus_no_chimera_ref.fasta --db reference_databases/uchime_sh_refs_ dynamic_develop_985_01.01.2016.ITS1.fasta 

# OTUs count
grep "^>" -c otus_no_chimera_ref.fasta

Map reads back to splitted reads

# map reads back to the read database using the USEARCH algorithm

/mnt/research/rdp/public/thirdParty/ usearch10.0.240_i86linux64 -usearch_global demultiplexed/splitted_R1/seqs_new.fasta -db clustered_OTU_ESV/otus_R1.fasta -strand plus -id 0.97 -otutabout clustered_OTU_ESV/otu_table_ITS_UPARSE_R1.txt

8) choosing the reference databases

There are several reference DB - some are cured and constantly updated some other not - the most common are:

  • UNITE for Fungi;
  • GreegGenes for Bacteria;
  • SILVA for Bacteria, Fungi and other Eukaryotes.

Alternatively you can build and use your own reference database.

9) assign taxonomy to OTUs representative sequences

A taxonomy is assigned to the OTUs representative sequences by comparing them to a reference. The most commonly used classifiers are:

  • UTAX algorithm in USEARCH (discontinued, but the most accurate!);
  • SINTAX current option in USEARCH;
  • RDP algorithm (standalone or QIIME embedded version);
  • CONSTAX consensus taxonomy for fungal ITS.

we are going to use the UTAX Algorithm

# assign taxonomy using UTAX
usearch -sintax reads.fastq -db 16s.udb -tabbedout reads.sintax \
  -strand both -sintax_cutoff 0.8

10) creating a .biom file

Some softwares (e.g., QIIME) require a biom tabe constructed using biom-fromat. A biom file contains the OTU counts and the associated metadata (e.g., taxonomy).

# create .biom file
biom convert -i otu_table.txt -o otu_table.biom --table-type="OTU table" --to-json

# add taxonomy to biom file
biom add-metadata -i otu_table.biom -o otu_table_tax.biom --observation-metadata-fp taxonomy_otutaxout__RDP.txt --observation-header OTUID,taxonomy,confidence --sc-separated taxonomy --float-fields confidence

Now try to read the otu_table_tax.biom

#read the biom
head otu_table_tax.biom
cat otu_table_tax.biom

how it displays?

# convert to json format again
biom convert -i otu_table_tax.biom -o otu_table_tax_json.biom --table-type="OTU table" --to-json

Reorder samples, converd and filter

#sort otu_table according sampleID
sort_otu_table.py -i otu_table_tax_json.biom -o otu_table_tax_sort.biom -m mapping_students.txt -s SampleID

# filter non fungal read counts - OTUs
filter_taxa_from_otu_table.py -i otu_table_tax_json.biom -o otu_table_tax_filt_json.biom -n p__Cercozoa,c__Mitochondria

# Convert biom to txt table with taxonomy
biom convert -i otu_table_tax_filt_json.biom -o otu_table_tax.txt --to-tsv --header-key taxonomy
